order=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f99891561167095>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>RE: Grouping as a shammy</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 27th 8:33 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>For the most part, in a tank heavy group buffs are not necessary.&nbsp;&nbsp;In such groups I just cast regen and speed on the tanks, and heal as needed.  Also cast regen on yourself and use canabalize.  Convert about 2/5 of your health to mana and then med and regen, you will regain mana much faster this way.  <br><br>Also never forget, if they get too bitchy, you can solo they can't.....&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>1 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table><tr><td colspan=2><ul><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f99972846688973>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=9&mid=99972846688973>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99972846688973>RE: Grouping as a shammy</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99972846688973#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Sep 5th 6:21 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Advice for when grouping: slow the mob. the damage taken by the tanks seems to be considerably less with a slowed mob than with a full speed baddie and healing. <br><br>Example: I was fighting in Trak's Teeth getting my Seb key and then in Kaesora at 45th trying to get a Howling Stones key with a few higher level friends. My strategy is to slow the mob as it came in. Basically this kept the main healer (druid) and myself at nearly full mana. 2 or more adds at once got me down to 50%, slowing, meleeing and blasting (the fights can be very fast for high level tanks and DoTs were not having full effect). No deaths, and only had to heal once or twice.<br><br>The adverse effect of this is that slowing a mob not engaged by melee-type often means aggro for you. High AC is the only way to handle this that I know of, since our dodge ability caps at 75. I usually have 720+ AC with my WIS gear and trying for 750+ with my "AC gear". The key seems to be the 01 of every hundred AC at this level, like 701 and 801. Avoiding spell damage needs those resists. (Resisting a shardwurm spell (even partially) gives me the warm fuzzies inside every time)<br><br>Don't confuse meleeing with tanking. A tank deals melee damage like you deal DoT damage. Meleeing keeps the mob in one place and let's you cannabalize during a fight (providing you have chloro or regen up. Be careful not to do this during raids or tough fights or as main healer, the cleric may need to heal the tank instead of helping you. Speaking with the cleric about how you cannabalize before fight is best way to develop startegy) as well as not attracting aggro from sitting too close to a dotted or hurt mob.<br><br>Debuffing may help lower the damage to yourself with multiple mobs aggroing on you, but I don't do it when soloing, so I haven't got much experience spending mana on incapacitate or such.<br><br>Keep Regen or Chloro up on the damage takers, as well as yourself and cannabalize. This keeps you gaining HPs even when you are puller (hey, suddenly I can solo, pull, melee, etc. I think I'm getting good at this) Since I seriously started using cannabalize I am more often with mana than without. With a cleric along, you won't be low mana ever, especially when (or if, I guess it's a rare drop, but both clerics I group with have it) they get celestial heal. Make sure you and the cleric understand how much mana you are using from him for the healing (I try to time the celestial heals so I can get off a couple cannabalizes in the middle of healing since it heals around 1300hp, which is where my hp's are when buffed)<br><br>Always melee when in a group, provided you won't be in the way. You need your defense skill up (I'm five points from cap of 200) and when you are there near the tank, the mob will not move when or if it aggros on you. Remember when that last mage/necro/whoever blasted the mob and it ran after them, making everyone chase it, as well as making the cleric run to heal the offending caster? Don't be the offending caster. I had been using virtually only 1HB until skill 160 or so, then found out the epic was a spear...so I've switched and now have skill up to 150+ and 2HB into the 70's. Once again, keep skills up or you will spend forever trying to get them where you want. If you can, and the tank is okay having to taunt the mob, blast em! Attract aggro when you have a group backing you up, my cleric friend has been doing that with just two of us to get his defense skill maxed out as well, since he knows we can always root and move away for a heal. <br><br>On another note, I am NOT experienced with raids to planes or Kael or other such uber places. I have also made it a habit to leave anything conning even or above alone. Please don't take this advice as such, where you need a main tank (main assist = MA) and secondary assists, it seems good for single group (and sometimes more than that) dungeon and outside zones so far. Kiting evens or yellows or reds is best left for druids and necros, IMHO. (Now that root actually works on mobs, I have taken to rooting and doting (Venom of Snake then Scourge, sometimes other way around if particular mob seems to be poison resistant) cannabalizing and running for solo work, I can take two low blues at a time this way, if I get an add) The best advice for new situations is to ask the group what it expects or wants you to do and experiment during the single pulls with what works best.<br><br>Halrog &lt;Elvar&gt;<br>45 Barbarian (and especially longwinded) Shaman<br>Bertoxx</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
